1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 51.1b of Title 74, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Targeted
5 Violence Prevention Act".
6 B. In furtherance of its core functions of prevention and
7 intelligence, response and recovery planning, and awareness and
8 preparedness, the Office of Homeland Security and the Oklahoma
9 Counter Terrorism Intelligence Center, a unit of the Office of
10 Homeland Security, may collect, analyze, and disseminate to law
11 enforcement and public safety agencies information concerning the
12 activity and identity of individuals reasonably suspected of
13 involvement in terrorism, targeted violence, threats to public
14 safety, or any other threats of organized or violent crime.
15 C. Any information disseminated pursuant to this section shall
16 be confidential and the recipients of such information shall comply
17 with the handling terms associated with the disclosure.
18 Unauthorized release or unauthorized use of information disseminated
19 pursuant to this section shall be a misdemeanor and shall be
20 punishable by incarceration in the county jail for a term not
21 exceeding one (1) year, or a fine not exceeding Fifty Thousand
22 Dollars ($50,000.00), or by both such fine and imprisonment. As
23 used in this subsection, "unauthorized release" or "unauthorized
24 use" shall include, but not be limited to, disseminating or
HB2720 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 disc losing confidential information in a manner which exceeds the
2 scope of the handling terms associated with the disclosure or in
3 violation of any rules promulgated pursuant to the authority of this
4 act. Provided, the following shall not constitute an unauthorized
5 release or unauthorized use of confidential information disseminated
6 pursuant to this section:
7 1. Sharing the confidential information with a law enforcement
8 officer or prosecutorial authority for use in a criminal
9 investigation or prosecution;
10 2. Sharing the confidential information, in exigent
11 circumstances, with leadership of the State or any political
12 subdivision, critical infrastructure personnel, or the target of any
13 threat; or
14 3. Sharing the confidential information with the express
15 authority of the Homeland Security Advisor or designee of the
16 Homeland Security Advisor.
17 D. Information collected or disseminated under the authority of
18 this section shall be privileged and not discoverable nor subject to
19 subpoena or order for production issued by any court, other than
20 production in a district court criminal proceeding for the
21 prosecution of crimes which are the subject of the information
22 sought.
